Now about the oft-cited Apollo program... Apollo was a race, a race to prove that American idealogy is better than Communist Russia's idealogy, and nothing more. Since developing new technology takes time, time they didn't have, mostly conventional technology was simply scaled up to meet the performance requirements. Further, the technology for RLVs and other such capabilities did not exsist: there was no DC-X or X-33 because there were no composit materials, high-speed fly by wire computers, etc - it couldn't be done.<br>
<br>
I think Bush's plan is quite reasonable if it can be pulled off. We today do not have the technology to go to Mars in any meaningful way; what is possible today is too slow, too small, and too dangerous to do anything beyond a half hearted attempt to look for bugs - in short, a Martial Apollo. Time and money directed to build life support systems, NEP and NTR engines, and most of all re-learn how to make reliable space ships and landers. If you had a space ship using today's &quot;50/50 chance of survival&quot; technology for a Mars trip and were selling $5 tickets, count me out. <br>
<br>
And why shouldn't the OSP program be &quot;stretched&quot; to go to the Moon? It takes two days to reach ISS, whats another day or two to get to Luna? And now that Nasa has time to build it right, a whole decade instead of half of one, it will be a real spaceship like the HL-20... why do you persist with visions of the X-38 &quot;winged eggshell&quot; or Lockheed's stupid &quot;falling bullet.&quot;? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stilgar@nuclearspace>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 98<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/04 1:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=993.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Barriers aren't that high</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Burt Rutan at Scaled, patron saint of the space libertarians, can hardly get a few hundred kilo human payload 60-odd miles up and back... </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
How long has he been trying?  The ship has been in construction for 2 years.  How long did the US government try? The mercury missions spanned 5 years.<br>
<br>
What were the resources used?  Scaled has (perhaps) 50 employees ( <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.scaled.com/images/staff.jpg">www.scaled.com/images/staff.jpg</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> )and a hangar at the Mojave airport.<br>
<br>
The US mercury missions &quot;saw more than 2,000,000 people from many major government agencies and much of the aerospace industry combine their skills, initiative, and experience into a national effort. &quot; (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www-pao.ksc.nasa.gov/history/mercury/mercury-overview.htm">www-pao.ksc.nasa.gov/hist...erview.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> )<br>
<br>
I'd say that overall, Scaled Composites produced significantly more than the US government per dollar spent on getting an individual into space.<br>
<br>
Scaled just had the first ever entirely privately funded supersonic flight. (The concorde recieved MASSIVE government subsidies from France)<br>
<br>
Further, Scaled Composites is not the only company trying for such goals.  There are dozens of others.<br>
<br>
Private industry is just more efficient than the government at development and construction.  That's just the way it is.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>a far, far cry from the hundred+ miles and orbital velocity needed, and thats just to get into orbit. Elon Musk at SpaceX and his Falcon-V multi engine rocket, which will take years to develop, can launch an underwhelming 9,200lbs to LEO... The smallest Delta-II can haul more then that measly five tons... if he can get his single-engine baby rocket to fly even once, and remember who is first customer is. Gravity is the ultimate barrier for entry.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Naturally the first few privately funded endeavors will be small compared to existing government systems.  That's to be expected.  What is also to be expected is that with private development, those systems will grow to market-determined sizes.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The non-government-funded space program is a pipe dream, a pipe dream best reserved for the latter portions of this century, because the technology does not exsist. When I say technology, I am talking about fundimentals of physics like light weight materials, new engine concepts, and the limits of what is practical to accomplish, not the engineering and the application of current technology like Scaled and SpaceX.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Are you saying that Scaled and SpaceX (and other associated companies... Xcor... Armadillo) didn't develop any new technology?  That they didn't (aren't) advancing the state of the art?  Surely you jest.<br>
<br>
Perhaps you're saying that the companies can't turn a profit because the technology for their business plans doesn't exist?  This is another obvious falsehood.<br>
<br>
Can you clarify what you mean or provide some evidence?  I'll happily provide testimony on the matter if you're really arguing what I think you're arguing... it'll just take some time to dig it all up.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Nor will it any time in the near future to permit a company to turn a profit on any space venture beyond satelite launch or tourist rides... there just isn't a signifigant source of wealth in space that can be accessed economicly, and so &quot;private industry&quot; will flounder until the technology does become available... and that will take time, a long time. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
It sounds like you're acknowledging that private companies will be able to turn a profit on satellite launches and tourist rides.  I think that's the point.  That's where the money is.  <br>
If you think that the technology developed in the pursuit of better efficiency at those tasks will have no application to other branches of space exploration, then I think you're grossly mistaken.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Since government is not accountable to the cruel task master of profit, the limits of what are practical are much less restrictive, hence it is practical now for Nasa to go to space in a meaningful way but not for businesses just yet. And now hopefully that Nasa has recieved the much-needed administrative kick in the pants, we'll get somewhere.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I think the key words in there are &quot;practical&quot; and &quot;meaningful.&quot;<br>
<br>
1|  Practical:<br>
I contend that it is currently impractical for NASA to fund a manned mission to Mars.  The costs as stated are astronomical and unjustified.  <br>
One way to reduce the costs is to look at where know you can save money.<br>
As far as energy requirements are concerned, LEO is about halfway to anywhere in the solar system.  If we can reduce the costs of getting material into LEO then the rest of the solar system, including Mars, will be opened up.  Assembly of larger ships can begin in orbit and they can be launched from the midpoint rather than from within the atmosphere.  Cutting the cost of LEO access drops the cost of Mars access, Venus access....  Alpha centauri access...  Everything.<br>
What has NASA done to reduce LEO access costs?<br>
Anything?  The shuttle? (HAHAHA!)  They were given the DC-X project... but we'll get to that later.  Basically, it is not in their intrest to reduce costs.  Their job as a government agency is to keep their budget as large as possible so they can keep as many people employed as feasible.  They are not an efficiency-driven organization.<br>
Anyway... I'm getting off topic.<br>
<br>
2| Meaningful:<br>
What would be meaningful?  A manned Mars base for the astronauts and scientists?  Perhaps.<br>
I think a manned Mars hotel would be far more meaningful.  Opening access to space to the everyday millionaire is by far the best way to get interest in space raised and keep interest (and therefore funding for new ventures) high.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Shuttle/ISS mess costs around $5Bn per year, and if you have that money freed up and you add it over a decade or so (the time between ISS completion and a return to the Moon), thats $50Bn... and with other programs being &quot;reprioritized&quot; and a few more billion a year reassigned, its not unthinkable to see almost $100Bn being practical with minimal budget increase... a decade or two is a long time.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I'll grant you that they can probably scrounge up the money without increasing funding too much... I think Bush said an increase of only a billion dollars.  Only.  There was a senator by the name of Dirkson who's famous for his quote (paraphrased) &quot;A billion here and a billion there, and pretty soon it adds up to real money.&quot;<br>
A billion may not seem like a lot when you're talking about a government project, but Xcor Aerospace built a fully functional rocketplane for half a million.  I mean... they had operational hardware on a budget that wouldn't even get you a 50 page report from NASA.  Shoot... it's less than NASA's <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>pastry</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> budget.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Now about the oft-cited Apollo program... Apollo was a race, a race to prove that American idealogy is better than Communist Russia's idealogy, and nothing more. Since developing new technology takes time, time they didn't have, mostly conventional technology was simply scaled up to meet the performance requirements. Further, the technology for RLVs and other such capabilities did not exsist: there was no DC-X or X-33 because there were no composit materials, high-speed fly by wire computers, etc - it couldn't be done.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I'll grant that. That really just means they should have spent more time on development instead of rushing through everything. Politics got in the way of natural technology development.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I think Bush's plan is quite reasonable if it can be pulled off. We today do not have the technology to go to Mars in any meaningful way; what is possible today is too slow, too small, and too dangerous to do anything beyond a half hearted attempt to look for bugs - in short, a Martial Apollo. Time and money directed to build life support systems, NEP and NTR engines, and most of all re-learn how to make reliable space ships and landers. If you had a space ship using today's &quot;50/50 chance of survival&quot; technology for a Mars trip and were selling $5 tickets, count me out.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
This all sounds reasonable to me except the first statement.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>And why shouldn't the OSP program be &quot;stretched&quot; to go to the Moon? It takes two days to reach ISS, whats another day or two to get to Luna?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
An interesting idea...  The energy requirements aren't that much greater.  The operational requirements, however, are pretty different.  Would you modify the vehicle to carry a LEM module equivalent that would be dropped off from lunar orbit and then recaptured?  That's a pretty different mission that launching a satelite.  Not impossible, but pretty difficult.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> And now that Nasa has time to build it right, a whole decade instead of half of one, it will be a real spaceship like the HL-20... why do you persist with visions of the X-38 &quot;winged eggshell&quot; or Lockheed's stupid &quot;falling bullet.&quot;?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Erm...  I didn't mention either of those... did someone else?<br>
<br>
Basically, I agree with some of what you say, but I think you dramatically understimate the potential of the private commercial space industry.  That is where the future of the space industry lies.  Space will never be popular (available to people) until costs drop.  Costs are not going to drop while the whole space industry is run, effectively, by the government.<br>
Once costs drop and your everyday upperclass individual can vacation on the orbiting hotel/casino every couple years, then we'll really be conquering space...  making it home.  <br>
